    def sinplot(n=10, flip=1):
    x = np.linspace(0, 14, 100)
    for i in range(1, n + 1):
        plt.plot(x, np.sin(x + i * .5) * (n + 2 - i) * flip)
        # Chart Title
        plt.title('Sinewaves') 
        # Watermark
        plt.figtext(x=0.88, y=0.12, s="©2023 Strictly Speaking", color='#546d78', 
        fontsize="x-small", weight='ultralight', ha='right', va='bottom', alpha=.20,
        transform=plt.gcf().transFigure) 

print(sinplot())
    def sinplot(n=10, flip=1): x = np.linspace(0, 14, 100) for i in range(1, n + 1): plt.plot(x, np.sin(x + i * .5) * (n + 2 - i) * flip) # Chart Title plt.title('Sinewaves') # Watermark plt.figtext(x=0.88, y=0.12, s="©2023 Strictly Speaking", color='#546d78', fontsize="x-small", weight='ultralight', ha='right', va='bottom', alpha=.20, transform=plt.gcf().transFigure) print(sinplot())

    Clean Data¶

    The SP 500 Pricing data requires a few modifications.

    1) Remove the leading spaces within column names.

    2) Change the date column from object type data to datetime data.

    In [7]:
    Copied! 
    spx_data.rename(columns=lambda x: x.strip(), inplace=True)
print(spx_data.columns)
    spx_data.rename(columns=lambda x: x.strip(), inplace=True) print(spx_data.columns)
    Index(['Date', 'Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close'], dtype='object')
